    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Yes, if you modify the response it will be directly taken in account for the hits. I made an example for you here:\r\n\r\nhttps://codesandbox.io/s/instantsearchjs-app-l3dft\r\n\r\n```js\r\nconst searchClient = {\r\n  search: function(requests) {\r\n    return algoliaSearchClient.search(requests).then(content => {\r\n      // do your api call here\r\n      const hits = content.results[0].hits;\r\n      console.log(hits);\r\n      return $.ajax('https://httpbin.org/anything', {\r\n        method: 'POST',\r\n        content: { hits },\r\n      }).then(res => {\r\n        // return from request\r\n        // content.results[0].hits = res\r\n        return content;\r\n      });\r\n    });\r\n  },\r\n  searchForFacetValues: function(requests) {\r\n    return algoliaSearchClient.searchForFacetValues(requests);\r\n  },\r\n};\r\n```\r\n\r\nas you can see, you need to make sure you \"modify\" the response from the regular js client\r\n",
